      explanation: "**Step 1:** Understand CP1's formal definition. For any two concurrent operations A and B applied at the same site, the transformed sequences transform(A,B); B and transform(B,A); A must produce identical document state. This is the convergence property — all sites must agree on the final state regardless of operation ordering.\\n\\n**Step 2:** Distinguish CP1 from CP2. CP1 handles two operations; CP2 handles three concurrent operations and requires transform(transform(A,B),C') = transform(transform(A,C),B'). CP2 is dramatically harder to satisfy correctly. Google Wave required both, making it notoriously complex.\\n\\n**Step 3:** Recognize practical implications. Google Docs sidesteps CP2 by using a single server that imposes a total order — only CP1 is needed. CRDT-based systems (Figma, Notion) also avoid CP2 entirely because their merge semantics are inherently commutative and associative.",
