      explanation: "**Step 1:** Contrast the two CRDT paradigms by their communication pattern. CvRDTs (state-based) periodically exchange full state snapshots — the merge function is the heart of the system. CmRDTs (operation-based) broadcast compact operation messages — the delivery requirements are the heart of the system.\\n\\n**Step 2:** Examine merge semantics. CvRDT merge must be commutative, associative, and idempotent — the three properties of a join-semilattice. These properties ensure that merging replicas A and B in any order always produces the same result. CvRDTs are safe for unreliable networks but O(state_size) per merge.\\n\\n**Step 3:** Compare delivery guarantees. CmRDTs require exactly-once causal delivery — if an operation is dropped or duplicated, convergence breaks. This is harder to guarantee than CvRDT's idempotent merge. Delta-state CRDTs bridge the gap: O(delta_size) efficiency with CvRDT-like safety.",
      hints: ["CvRDT merges 'what the state looks like'; CmRDT sends 'what changed'.", "If your network can guarantee causal delivery with no duplicates, CmRDT is more efficient; if not, CvRDT's idempotent merge is safer."],
